On this guide, it shows that the container registry should be deployed in the same VNet, however, in [this guide](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/how-to-secure-inferencing-vnet?tabs=python#limitations) under limitations it says that to use ACI deployments, the container registry should not be in the same VNet. Should the guide not warn the user of this nuance? Also, what is the deployment strategy for a secure deployment? Should the container registry be public? Does it require its own vnet and use peering?

Release notes

Sourced from ajv's releases.

v6.12.6

Fix performance issue of "url" format.

v6.12.5

Fix uri scheme validation (@​ChALkeR). Fix boolean schemas with strictKeywords option (#1270)

v6.12.4

Fix: coercion of one-item arrays to scalar that should fail validation (failing example).

v6.12.3

Pass schema object to processCode function Option for strictNumbers (@​issacgerges, #1128) Fixed vulnerability related to untrusted schemas (CVE-2020-15366)

v6.12.2

Removed post-install script

v6.12.1

Docs and dependency updates

v6.12.0

Improved hostname validation (@​sambauers, #1143) Option keywords to add custom keywords (@​franciscomorais, #1137) Types fixes (@​boenrobot, @​MattiAstedrone) Docs:

  • error logging example (@​RadiationSickness)
  • TypeScript usage notes (@​thetric)

v6.11.0

Time formats support two digit and colon-less variants of timezone offset (#1061 , @​cjpillsbury) Docs: RegExp related security considerations Tests: Disabled failing typescript test

employees access AzureML from a Private Endpoint and virtual network?

The consequence of this guide: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/tutorial-create-secure-workspace

Is that you get a Data Science VM that cannot get Microsoft corporate policies pushed down onto it (since the image is missing things policy wants to manipulate) so therefore it cannot domain join and therefore cannot enter Azure. Following similar procedures for a Windows 10 VM yields errors that prevent you from connecting to the workspace, noting: 

```
Your request for data was not sent. Here are some things to try: Check your network and internet connection, make sure a proxy server is not blocking your connection, check if you have an ad blocker turned on
```

In the doc of https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/how-to-secure-workspace-vnet?tabs=pe#prerequisites, it says "Your Azure Container Registry must be in the same virtual network and subnet as the storage account and compute targets used for training or inference."

Gary
